I"1<h1 id="topic-ideas">Topic Ideas</h1>
<p>Here is a short list of some specific ideas for topics we might pursue for one of our meetings.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ismat Chughtai, <a href="https://www.rekhta.org/stories/lihaaf-ismat-chughtai-stories?lang=hi"><em>Lihāf</em></a>. A story about female homosexuality that made Ismat “notorious” among her more orthodox contemporaries, even those in the Progressive Writers’ Association. In fact, modern progressive readers might also have some qualms with Ismat’s depiction of homosexuality…?</li>
<li>Ismat Chughtai, <a href="https://www.rekhta.org/stories/hindustan-chhor-do-ismat-chughtai-stories?lang=hi"><em>Hindustān Chhoṛ Do</em></a>. A compassionate story about a Britisher left behind in post-Independence India.</li>
<li>Miraji, <a href="https://www.rekhta.org/nazms/clerk-kaa-nagma-e-mohabbat-sab-raat-mirii-sapnon-men-guzar-jaatii-hai-aur-main-sotaa-huun-meeraji-nazms?lang=hi"><em>Klark Kā Nagmā-e-Mohabbat</em></a>. It’s a love poem, I suppose, but it’s also a muted paean to the downtrodden everyman.</li>
<li>Safdar Hashmi, <a href="https://archive.org/details/DuniyaSabki-Hindi"><em>Duniya Sabkī</em></a>. Simple and fun children’s poems with lots of enjoyable rhyme and meter, by a writer who’s sort of a martyr-figure for the Indian Left. The title poem reflects some of his politics, as does <em>Rajū aur Kajū</em>. <em>Bāṃsurīwālā</em> is a rendition of the Pied Piper of Hamlin, with a bit of a democratic spin at the end. The last poem, <em>Peṛ</em>, is a call to end environmental exploitation.</li>
<li>Safdar Hashmi, <em>Hallā Bol</em>. It could be fun to try to act out this play together, if we can get our hands on the text of the play… I haven’t been able to find it on the internet.</li>
<li>Please feel free to suggest more!</li>
</ul>
